result.execSummary:
The defendant Ashley A Dolan was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Methamphetamine [Modifiers: Repeater], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(g).
  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer [Modifiers: Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

9:09 am Def in court w/ Atty Sean William O'Neill.  Def in custody.  Emily E. Hynek appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
O'Neill:  She's served her previous time.  The only thing holding her in jail now is the 2 cash bonds.  These 2 cases are set for a plea.  She's had 80 days of sobriety.  Her record is mostly misdemeanor based.  It's not a terrible record.  She would live with her mother on Brice Prairie.  No obj. to JSS monitoring.  She has 2 children who are being taken care of by her mother.  Her mother has cancer and is dying.  She's been on JSS before and did not violated.  Asks for a sig. bond.  It's set for a plea but we don't have anything definitively worked out.  COURT:  Has there been a compass report?  O'Neill:  No.  COURT:  Monitoring is one thing but with no treatment plan, it's setting her up for failure.  O'Neill:  She had an assessment on probation and that showed she was dependent.  There's no reason she can't do it again.  Hynek:  It's true her history is all misdemeanors but she was revoked off probation.  Given her drug addiction, I have concerns with her ability to be out in the communit without a set plan being in place.  I'm not taking a strong position but if shs'e released, I'd ask for house arrest and drug testing.
COURT:  I'd like JSS to have a treatment plan such as the on as part of probation.  Once I have that, I'll reduce it to a $1,000 sign bond with the condition that she follow the treatment plan she had on probation.  JSS monitor house arrest and drug testing.  No alcohol or controlled substances w/o Rx from a Dr.  She's to sign any releases so that JSS can verify her compliance.
Court addresses Ms. Dolan.
